To run the Playwright end-to-end tests using the "Executor" target in a `project.json` file in an Angular application, you can follow these steps:

1. **Install Playwright:**
   First, you need to install Playwright and its Angular integration. Run the following command to install Playwright and its dependencies:

   ```sh
   npm install -D @playwright/test playwright
   ```

2. **Create a playwright config file:**
   You can create a configuration file for Playwright, `playwright.config.ts` or `playwright.config.js`, in your project root. This file is optional but recommended for configuring your Playwright tests.

   ```ts
   // playwright.config.ts or playwright.config.js
   import { defineConfig } from '@playwright/test';

   export default defineConfig({
     // Add your Playwright configuration here
   });
   ```

3. **Modify `project.json` to add the Executor:**
   In your `project.json` file, you can add a new target named "Executor" that will run your Playwright end-to-end tests. Update the JSON with the new executor configuration:

   ```json
   {
     "$schema": "https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/aspnet/framework/worker-templates/schema/json/project.json",
     "version": "1.0.0",
     "minimumFramework": "4.0",
     "projectType": "web",
     "dependencies": {
       // Dependencies for your project
     },
     "frameworks": {
       "web": {
         "runtime": "node",
         "fileWatchers": ["tsconfig.web.json", "tsconfig.spec.json"]
       }
     },
     "configurations": {
       "production": {
         "build": {
           "environmentVariables": {
             "API_BASE_URL": "https://api.example.com"
           }
         }
       }
     },
     "architect": {
       "default": {
         "command": "npm run build", "type": "bundle", "problemMatcher": "none"
       },
       "extract-i18n": {
         "command": "npm run extract-i18n", "type": "aspnet", "dependsOn": ["build"], "problemMatcher": "$msCompile"
       },
       "unit-test": {
         "command": "npm test -- --watch", "type": "npm", "dependsOn": ["build"]
       }
     },
     "executors": {
       "Executor": {
         "options": {
           "command": "npx playwright test --mode=e2e"
         }
       }
     }
   }
   ```

4. **Add a `task.json` file (optional):**
   Additionally, you can create a `task.json` file at the root of your project to define custom tasks and allow you to use the executor to run these tasks.

   ```json
   {
     "version": "2.0.0",
     "runTargets": {
       "build": {
         "command": "npm run build",
         "isBackground": true
       },
       "e2e": {
         "command": "npx playwright test --mode=E2E",
         "dependsOn": ["build"]
       }
     },
     "targets": {
       "build": {
         "command": "npm run build",
         "type": "npm"
       },
       "e2e": {
         "command": "npx playwright test --mode=E2E",
         "type": "npm",
         "dependsOn": ["build"]
       }
     }
   }
   ```

5. **Run your test using the Executor:**
   Finally, run your Playwright E2E tests using the new Executor target by executing:

   ```sh
   dotnet sln MyProject.sln build --configuration Production --executor Executor
   dist/YourApp/dist/YourApp dist/YourApp.spa dist/YourApp.pwa dist/YourApp-pwa
   dist/YourApp-sspa/YourApp/YourApp.js dist/YourApp-sspa/YourApp.pwa dist/YourApp-sspa-pwa
   dist/YourApp/YourApp.js dist/YourApp.pwa dist/YourApp-pwa
   dist/YourApp-pwa yourapp-main-pwa-staging.umd.js dist/yourapp-main-pwa-staging.wasm dist/yourapp-main-pwa-staging.pwa-dist
   dist/E2EPWA/YourApp/YourApp.pwa dist/E2EPWA/YourApp-main.pwa dist/E2EPWA/YourApp-staging.pwa dist/E2EPWA/YourApp-pwa dist/E2EPWA/YourApp-unix-staging.umd.js
   dist/production/yourapp-main.wasm dist/E2EPWA/yourapp-main.umd.js dist/E2EPWA/yourapp-main-pwa-staging.umd.js dist/E2EPWA/yourapp-main.umd-wasm.js dist/production/yourapp-pwa.js dist/production/yourapp-main.pwa dist/production/yourapp-pwa-dist
   ```

This setup will enable you to run your Playwright E2E tests using the Executor specified in your `project.json` as a target for your build process.

**Note:** The exact file paths and commands might vary based on your project's configuration and structure. Adjust them as necessary to suit your needs.

