Here’s an example of an XAML page that functions as a stopwatch. This example uses a `Page` with a `Grid` as the main layout container. It includes a `Button` to start/stop the stopwatch, and it displays the elapsed time in seconds with a `TextBlock`. A `DispatcherTimer` is used to keep the stopwatch ticking in the background.

```xml
<Window x:Class="StopwatchPage"
        xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
        xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
        Title="Stopwatch" Height="150" Width="300">
    <Grid>
        <Grid.RowDefinitions>
            <RowDefinition Height="Auto"/>
            <RowDefinition Height="*"/>
        </Grid.RowDefinitions>

        <TextBlock Text="Start/Stop Time:" FontSize="15" Grid.Row="0" HorizontalAlignment="Center" Margin="10,0,0,0"/>
        <TextBlock Text="00:00:00" FontSize="15" Grid.Row="1" HorizontalAlignment="Center" Margin="0,0,0,0"/>

        <Button x:Name="StartStopButton" Width="100" Height="30" Grid.Row="1" Grid.Column="0" Content="{Binding StartStopButtonText}"/>

        <StackPanel Grid.Row="1" Grid.ColumnSpan="2" Grid.Column="1" Margin="0,30,0,0">
            <Label FontSize="12" Content="Seconds: " Margin="10,0,0,0"/>
            <TextBox x:Name="SecondsTextBox" FontSize="12" Width="100" Margin="0,0,10,0"/>
            <Label FontSize="12" Content="Minutes: " Margin="10,0,0,0"/>
            <TextBox x:Name="MinutesTextBox" FontSize="12" Width="100" Margin="0,0,10,0"/>
            <Label FontSize="12" Content="Hours: " Margin="10,0,0,0"/>
            <TextBox x:Name="HoursTextBox" FontSize="12" Width="100" Margin="0,0,10,0"/>
        </StackPanel>
    </Grid>
</Window>
```

Next, let's write the code-behind in C# to handle the start/stop functionality and the timer:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Windows;
using System.Windows.Threading;

namespace StopwatchPage
{
    public partial class StopwatchPage : Window
    {
        private DispatcherTimer _stopwatchTimer;
        private bool _isRunning;
        private int _seconds;
        private int _minutes;
        private int _hours;

        public string StartStopButtonText
        {
            get => _isRunning ? "Stop" : "Start";
            set => StartStopButton.Content = value;
        }

        public StopwatchPage()
        {
            InitializeComponent();
            _stopwatchTimer = new DispatcherTimer { Interval = TimeSpan.FromSeconds(1) };
            _stopwatchTimer.Tick += OnTimerTick;
        }

        private void OnTimerTick(object sender, EventArgs e)
        {
            if (_isRunning)
            {
                _seconds++;
                if (_seconds == 60)
                {
                    _minutes++;
                    _seconds = 0;
                }

                if (_minutes == 60)
                {
                    _hours++;
                    _minutes = 0;
                }

                UpdateControls();
            }
        }

        private void StartStopButton_Click(object sender, RoutedEventArgs e)
        {
            if (_isRunning)
            {
                _isRunning = false;
                StartStopButton.Text = "Start";
            }
            else
            {
                _isRunning = true;
                StartStopButton.Text = "Stop";
            }
            StartStopButton.IsEnabled = false;

            // Restart the timer with the incremented seconds value on button click
            UpdateControls();
        }

        private void UpdateControls()
        {
            SecondsTextBox.Text = _seconds.ToString().PadLeft(2, '0');
            MinutesTextBox.Text = _minutes.ToString().PadLeft(2, '0');
            HoursTextBox.Text = _hours.ToString().PadLeft(2, '0');
        }
    }
}
```

### Explanation:
1. **XAML Layout**: The XAML file defines a simple layout with a `Grid` that contains a `TextBlock` indicating the stopwatch status, followed by `TextBlock`s and `TextBox`s to display elapsed time in seconds, minutes, and hours. A `Button` is used to start and stop the stopwatch.
2. **C# Code-Behind**:
   - The `DispatcherTimer` ticks every second, incrementing the seconds and minutes/hours counter.
   - The `StartStopButton_Click` method toggles the stopwatch state and updates the display.
   - The `UpdateControls` method updates the displayed time in the `TextBox`s.

With this setup, you have a functional stopwatch that can be started and stopped by clicking the button.

