Title: Building a Chrome Extension: A Comprehensive How-To Guide

---

# Chapter 1: Introduction

In this guide, we will teach you how to create a Chrome extension from scratch. The extension we will be creating performs a simple yet essential task: converting text on web pages to uppercase. By the end of this guide, you will have a working Chrome extension that you can tweak, update, and personalize according to your needs.

## What are Chrome Extensions

Chrome extensions are small software programs that enhance the functionality of the Google Chrome web browser. Extensions range from productivity tools to themes, and most importantly, they can interact with the websites you browse. In this guide, you will learn how to create a content script that interacts directly with the content you see in your Chrome browser.

# Chapter 2: Prerequisites

To follow along with this guide, you will need:

- A computer with Google Chrome installed. If you do not have it, it can be downloaded for free on [the Chrome website](https://www.google.com/chrome/).
- A code editor. Some good options include Sublime Text, Visual Studio Code, Atom, Brackets, etc. This guide prefers [Visual Studio Code](https://code.visualstudio.com/).
- Basic knowledge of HTML, CSS, and JavaScript.

# Chapter 3: Manifest File

A manifest file (`manifest.json`) is a JSON file containing metadata that Chrome needs to load and run your extension properly. Let's create one now.

```json
{
  "manifest_version": 2,
  "name": "Uppercase Converter",
  "version": "1.0",
  "description": "A Chrome extension that converts text to uppercase",
  "icons": {
    "16": "icon16.png",
    "48": "icon48.png",
    "128": "icon128.png"
  },
  "default_locale": "en",
  "background": {
    "scripts": ["background.js"],
    "persistent": false
  },
  "content_scripts": [
    {
      "matches": ["*://*/*"],
      "js": ["content-script.js"]
    }
  ],
  "permissions": [
    "activeTab"
  ]
}
```

In our `manifest.json`, we define:

- **manifest_version 2**: The version of the manifest file format.
- **name**: The name of our extension.
- **version**: The version of our extension.
- **description**: A brief description of what our extension does.
- **icons**: Path and sizes of the extension's icons. These come in three sizes (16x16, 48x48, and 128x128) and are used in the Chrome menu and the install page. Make sure you actually have an `icon16.png`, an `icon48.png`, and an `icon128.png` in your `icons` folder.
- **default_locale**: The default language displayed in the extension's user interface. Here, we set it to English (en).
- **background**: This field specifies that our extension uses a background script. The `scripts` key holds the path to the script in the extension folder. The `persistent` flag specifies whether the script needs to be loaded as a background page (as a separate tab with its own document & its own window/tab). Since we want our background script to start when you launch the extension, we set it to false.
- **content_scripts**: These fields define scripts that run in the context of the webpage. Our script will run for all web pages (`"*://*/*"`), so that no webpage is excluded.
- **permissions**: The `activeTab` permission lets our extension access the tab your focused on at that moment. This allows our script to read the web page's text and transform it when needed.

# Chapter 4: Background Script

The background script (`background.js`) is where we can keep the logic for our extension. For our simple uppercase converter, we don't need anything in this file initially.

```javascript
chrome.runtime.onInstalled.addListener(function() {
  console.log("Uppercase Converter installed.");
});
```

This script only logs a message when our Extension gets installed.

# Chapter 5: Content Script

The content script (`content-script.js`) is where we perform our main operations. In this case, we want to convert the text on a webpage to uppercase. Let's write the script.

```javascript
// Function to convert text to uppercase
function convertToUpperCase() {
  Array.from(document.querySelectorAll('body *')).forEach(function(node) {
    node.innerText = node.innerText.toUpperCase();
  });
}

// Function that will convert the text
function convertText() {
  let [tab] = await chrome.tabs.query({ active: true, currentWindow: true });
  convertToUpperCase(tab.body.innerHTML);
}

chrome.runtime.onMessage.addListener(function(request, sender, sendResponse) {
  if (request.command === "convert") {
    convertText();
  }
});
```

**Explanation:**

- We define two functions: `convertToUpperCase` and `convertText`.
- Within `convertToUpperCase`, we get all elements in the document using `document.querySelectorAll('body *')`.
- Then, we map each element to convert its inner text to uppercase.
- `convertText` first retrieves the active tab using the `chrome.tabs.query` method.
- After that, we call `convertToUpperCase`, passing the inner HTML of tab body, which will convert all the text to uppercase.
- We also listen to the `chrome.runtime.onMessage.addListener` event to respond to a message from the popup or options page. When we get a message with the command "convert", we call `convertText`.

# Chapter 6: Popup

A popup is a small user interface displayed on the top of your Chrome browser when you click on your extension icon. Let's build one now.

First, create a folder structure as follows:

```
-- popup
   -- popup.html
   -- popup.js
```

Now, create the `popup.html` file with the following content:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <style>
      body {
        width: 300px;
        height: 100px;
        margin: 10px;
      }
      .button-container {
        text-align: center;
      }
      button {
        margin: 5px;
        font-size: 15px;
      }
    </style>
  </head>
  <body>
    <h1>Uppercase Converter</h1>
    <div class="button-container">
      <button id="convert">Convert</button>
    </div>
    <script src="popup.js"></script>
  </body>
</html>
```

And, create `popup.js` with the following code:

```javascript
document.getElementById('convert').addEventListener('click', async () => {
  chrome.tabs.query({ active: true, currentWindow: true }, (tabs) => {
    chrome.runtime.sendMessage({ command: 'convert' });
  });
});
```

**Explanation:**

- In `popup.html`, we add styling to make our button look good. We also have a `Convert` button.
- In `popup.js`, we add an event listener to our `Convert` button.
- When you click on the `Convert` button, we retrieve the active tab.
- And we send a message to our background script saying `{ command: 'convert' }`.

# Chapter 7: Option Page

Option pages let you configure a Chrome extension. Let's create an options page now.

First, create a new folder called `options`, and inside it create three files: `options.html`, `options.js` and `icon16.png`.

Let's create the content of `options.html` and `options.js` as shown below:

```html
<!-- options/options.html -->
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <title>Options</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <h1>Options</h1>
    <label for="mode">Mode: </label>
    <select id="mode">
      <option value="uppercase" selected>Uppercase</option>
      <option value="lowercase">Lowercase</option>
    </select>
    <br><br>
    <button id="save">Save Changes</button>
    <script src="options.js"></script>
  </body>
</html>
```

```javascript
// options/options.js
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', (event) => {
  if (document.getElementById('mode') !== null) {
    document.getElementById('mode').addEventListener('change', async (e) => {
      chrome.runtime.sendMessage({ command: 'update' });
    });
  }

  if (document.getElementById('save') !== null) {
    document.getElementById('save').addEventListener('click', async () => {
      chrome.storage.local.set({ mode: document.getElementById('mode').value });
      window.close();
    });
  }
});
```

**Explanation:**

- In options.html, we create a basic drop-down to pick between `uppercase` and `lowercase` modes, along with a `Save Changes` button.
- Inside options.js, we listen for changes in the mode dropdown and sends a message to the main script with `{ command: 'update' }`.
- We also send a message to the main script when the `Save Changes` button is pressed, to do the necessary operations.

# Chapter 8: Icons

The `icons` folder should contain images with these resolutions – to display on the Chrome toolbar, in the `chrome://extensions/` page when you have your extension installed, and in the `newtab.html` page when you create a `manifest.json` with the `"chrome_action"` key (if your extension has a "Pinned by bookmarks" right-click menu icon, by default).

```plaintext
- "icon16.png" (16x16 pixels)
- "icon48.png" (48x48 pixels)
- "icon128.png" (128x128 pixels)
```

- Use any icon here. This can even be an ICO file containing all of the three icons, but if there are multiple of the same size (for example, an 80x32 pixels black 16x16 icon), make sure that they are in the directory before 48x48 or 128x128 files.

# Chapter 9: Final Instructions

Now that you have followed all of the steps in this guide, you should have the following files in your extension folder:

```plaintext
Uppercase-Extension
|
|-- icon16.png
|-- icon48.png
|-- icon128.png
|
|-- manifest.json
|-- background.js
|-- content-script.js
|-- popup
|   |-- popup.html
|   `-- popup.js
|-- options
|   |-- options.html
|   `-- options.js
```

Run the extension by clicking the "Load unpacked" button in Chrome's Extensions page (`chrome://extensions/`). Select your project folder here.

To test your extension, open a website of your choice. Click your extension icon, and change the mode selection to "lowercase". If you press the `Convert` button, text in the website should now match your selected mode.

# Chapter 10: Additional Resources

- [Developing an Extension](https://developers.google.com/extensions/): A thorough guide
- [Publishing an Extension](https://developers.google.com/extensions/developing/publishing): Information on publishing your extension to the Chrome Web Store
- [Chrome Extension Programming – Chrome API Documentation](https://developer.chrome.com/extensions/api): A detailed API reference
- [Chrome Extension Development Tutorial](https://www.javascript-tutorials.com/building-chrome-extensions-with-javascript/): A straightforward tutorial to help you get started

We hope you've enjoyed this guide on how to build a Chrome extension. Stay tuned for more guides on using Google Chrome's advanced features. Good luck!

