Firstly, ensure your `bsa` and `bsa_cancel` scripts (`bsa` and `bsa_cancel`) properly handle the MFA challenge and subsequent verification responses:

```bash
exec bsa { 
    wait = yes
    input_pairs = request
    output_pairs = reply
    program = "/usr/bin/java -cp /etc/freeradius/3.0/mods-available/bsa-authenticator/lib/* -Dlogback.configurationFile=/etc/freeradius/3.0/mods-available/bsa-authenticator/config/logback.xml -DbsaType=request -DbsaURL=https://example.com -DbsaClientKey=clientKey -DbsaID='%{User-Name}' com.app.auth.Authenticator"
    shell_escape = yes
    timeout = 30
}

exec bsa_cancel { 
    wait = yes
    input_pairs = request
    output_pairs = reply
    program = "/usr/bin/java -cp /etc/freeradius/3.0/mods-available/bsa-authenticator/lib/* -Dlogback.configurationFile=/etc/freeradius/3.0/mods-available/bsa-authenticator/config/logback.xml -DbsaType=cancel -DbsaURL=https://example.com -DbsaClientKey=clientKey -DbsaID='%{User-Name}' com.app.auth.Authenticator"
    shell_escape = yes
    timeout = 30
}
```

Next, let's simplify and improve the `post-auth` block in your `/etc/freeradius/3.0/sites-available/default` file. Here's the improved version:

```plaintext
# OpenLDAP settings (if necessary, adjust other settings as per your environment)

# Authentication settings
Auth-Type BSA {
 bsa
}

Auth-Type LDAP {
 ldap
}

# Post-auth
post-auth {
 update locals {
  reply:Auth-Type := Auth-Type
  Reply-Message := reply:Reply-Message

  # Check if the auth is BSA
  if (reply:Auth-Type == "Reject") then {
    LDAP-Group-Name := reply:Reply-Message
    if ("cn=.,cn=(.\*,ou=Client,dc=dev-ldap,dc=fnsmalaysia,dc=com") =~ LDAP-Group-Name then {
          reply:Reply-Message := "MFA required."
       } else {
          update reply{
            Reply-Message := "Unknown group name."
          }
     }
  }
 }

 # If the user authenticated successfully, we continue with BSA or just log in directly.
 if (reply:Auth-Type == "LDAP") then {
 reply{
  Auth-Type := "BSA"
  Reply-Message := reply:Reply-Message
 }
 } else if (reply:Reply-Message = "MFA required.") then {
 reply{
  Auth-Type := "BSA"
  Reply-Message := reply:Reply-Message
  post = bsa
  session-auth = 1
  reply {
     Error-Message := Reply-Message
  }
}
 } else {
 reply{
  Auth-Type := reply:Auth-Type
  Reply-Message := reply:Reply-Message
 }
}
}
```

Explanation:
- In the `post-auth` section, we first update local variables as usual.
- Check if the authentication type is `BSA`, then determine if MFA (BSA) is required.
- If the group name is found as expected (`cn=.,cn=(.\*,ou=Client,dc=dev-ldap,dc=fnsmalaysia,dc=com`), update the `Reply-Message` to indicate MFA is required and respond with `Auth-Type= BSA`: set `post = bsa` to handle BSA and authenticate the user after BSA completion.
- Otherwise, handle a wrong group name (or other errors).
- Continue to authenticate the user via LDAP or BSA as required.

Note: Adjust the regex patterns and error messages as they might differ based on your precise LDAP configuration.

After adjusting the `post-auth` logic as described, you should now be setting MFA (BSA) only when necessary and properly chaining requests in a manner consistent with your overall authentication workflows.

Make sure the Java module is properly set up, and verify the BSA (MFA) script outputs match what is required at each step.

