To obtain the current page title using the WordPress REST API with authentication in Next.js, you need to make an authenticated GET request to the `/wp-json/wp/v2/sites/{siteId}/pages` endpoint, where `{siteId}` is the ID of the WordPress site for which you want to get the pages. You can then parse the response and extract the page titles.

Here's an example of how to fetch pages and extract page titles in a Next.js app using `axios` and async/await:

1. Install `axios` (if you haven't already):

```sh
npm install axios
```

2. In your Next.js component, setup the authentication credentials and call the WordPress API:

```javascript
import axios from 'axios';

export async function getServerSideProps() {
  const siteId = 'your_site_id'; // Replace with your WordPress site ID
  const url = `https://yourwebsite.com/wp-json/wp/v2/sites/${siteId}/pages`;

  // Replace `your_token` with your actual WordPress REST API token.
  const auth = 'Bearer your_token';

  try {
    const response = await axios.get(url, { headers: { Authorization: auth } });

    // Extract the titles from the response
    const pages = response.data.map(page => {
      return page;
    });

    // You now have an array of pages with their titles
    // In Next.js, you can send the pages as props to your page component
    return { props: { pages: pages } };
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error fetching pages', error);
    return { props: { error: 'Error fetching pages' } };
  }
}

const Page = ({ pages }) => {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Pages</h1>
      <ul>
        {pages.map(page => (
          <li key={page.id}>
            <strong>{page.title.rendered}</strong> - {page.url}
          </li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </div>
  );
};

export default Page;
```

In this code snippet:

- We setup the `getServerSideProps` function that will run on each request.
- We define the URL to the WordPress REST API endpoint for fetching pages. Replace `your_site_id` and `https://yourwebsite.com` with your actual site ID and WordPress site URL.
- We set up the Bearer token authentication for the request. Replace `your_token` with your actual WordPress REST API token.
- We fetch the page data and transform it into a simpler array that only has the object itself.
- We pass the `pages` prop to the component, which will render the list of pages and their titles.

This will run on the server-side, so the client's browser will only see the page with the list of pages and will not have to perform the login or HTTP request process. Next.js will handle the fetch and pass the resulting props to your page component for rendering. Remember to handle any errors that may occur during the fetch.

