Dependency-injection is a software design pattern that deals with how components get hold of their dependencies. In Spring Framework, dependency injection is a core feature that allows Spring to control the instantiation and the lifecycle of the beans. This means Spring manages the objects (or beans) that a class uses (dependencies). Instead of a class creating its own dependencies, Spring will auto-inject them. This can be done in various ways, which Spring calls as IoC (Inversion of Control) containers.

In Spring Framework, there are three main types of dependency injection (DI):

1. Constructor-based DI
2. Method-based DI
3. Field-based DI

**Constructor-based DI (Dependency Injection through Constructors):**
Constructor-based injection is perhaps the most common way to inject dependencies in Spring. Here, Spring automatically calls the constructor or constructor with parameters to inject the required dependencies into the bean at the time of its creation.

```java
@Component
public class CoffeeService {

    private final CoffeeMaker coffeeMaker;

    @Autowired
    public CoffeeService(CoffeeMaker coffeeMaker) {
        this.coffeeMaker = coffeeMaker;
    }

    // Use coffeeMaker to make coffee...
}
```

**Method-based DI (Dependency Injection through Methods):**
Instead of injecting through the constructor, dependencies are supplied as arguments to methods, especially lifecycle methods such as `@PostConstruct`, `@PreDestroy` or application events. The method should be either void or return void.

```java
@Component
public class CoffeeService {

    private CoffeeMaker coffeeMaker;

    @Autowired
    public void setCoffeeMaker(CoffeeMaker coffeeMaker) {
        this.coffeeMaker = coffeeMaker;
    }

    // Use coffeeMaker to make coffee...
}
```

**Field-based DI (Dependency Injection through Fields):**
In this approach, field injection is used. It is less preferred due to being less test-friendly and less explicit than using constructors. However, annotations like `@Autowired` are still necessary.

```java
@Component
public class CoffeeService {

    @Autowired
    private CoffeeMaker coffeeMaker;

    // Use coffeeMaker to make coffee...
}
```

In summary, Spring’s dependency injection is all about reducing the dependency management and promoting loose coupling between classes. By having dependencies injected by Spring at runtime (inversion of control), classes are not responsible for their creation or configuration, making them more modular, easier to test, and flexible to changes.

