To achieve the desired behavior, we can leverage the Intersection Observer API to detect when the navigation bar comes into or falls out of the viewport and toggle its visibility and animation accordingly. The `sliding` animation can be disabled for pages that do not scroll much and a little slack can be set for triggering these actions.

Here's a sample implementation:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <style>
    body {
      margin: 0;
      font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
    }
    .navbar {
      position: fixed;
      top: -60px; /* Initially hidden */
      width: 100%;
      background-color: #333;
      color: #fff;
      transition: top 0.2s;
      z-index: 100; /* Ensure it's on top */
    }
    .content {
      padding-top: 60px; /* Space for the hidden navbar */
      padding-bottom: 50px; /* Space for the footer */
    }
    .footer {
      position: fixed;
      bottom: 0;
      width: 100%;
      background-color: #333;
      color: #fff;
      text-align: center;
      padding: 10px 0;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>

  <div class="navbar">Navigation Bar</div>
  <div class="content">
    <button style="position: absolute; top: 0; right: 0; padding: 10px; background: #333; color: #fff;">Scroll Down</button>
    <!-- Content goes here -->
  </div>
  <div class="footer">Footer Content</div>

  <script>
    let lastScrollTop = 0;
    const navbar = document.querySelector('.navbar');
    const content = document.querySelector('.content');
    const scrollDownButton = document.querySelector('button');

    function removeScrollDownButton() {
      scrollDownButton.style.display = 'none';
    }

    function showScrollDownButton() {
      scrollDownButton.style.display = 'block';
    }

    const options = {
      root: null,
      rootMargin: '0px',
      threshold: 0.0
    };

    const observer = new IntersectionObserver(function(entries, observer) {
      entries.forEach(entry => {
        const currentScrollTop = window.pageYOffset || document.documentElement.scrollTop;

        if (entry.intersectionRatio > 0.1) {
          if (currentScrollTop > lastScrollTop) {
            // Scrolled down, slide back the navbar and hide the scroll down button
            navbar.style.top = '-60px';
            removeScrollDownButton();
          } else if (currentScrollTop < lastScrollTop) {
            // Scrolled up, slide the navbar back in and show the scroll down button
            navbar.style.top = '0';
            showScrollDownButton();
          }
        }
        lastScrollTop = currentScrollTop <= 0 ? 0 : currentScrollTop; // For Mobile or negative scrolling
      });
    }, options);

    observer.observe(document.querySelector('.content') || document);

    // Listen for scroll events to force the animation when scrolling up and down
    window.onscroll = function() {
      if (Math.abs(window.pageYOffset - lastScrollTop) > 50) {
        navbar.style.top = window.pageYOffset > 0 ?
          `-${window.pageYOffset / 2}px` :
          '-60px';
        lastScrollTop = window.pageYOffset;
      }
    };
  </script>

  <style>
    /* Scroll down button styles */
    button {
      position: fixed;
      right: 0;
      top: 0;
      padding: 10px;
      background: #333;
      color: #fff;
      border: none;
      cursor: pointer;
      display: none; /* Hidden by default */
    }
  </style>

</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
1. **HTML Structure:** Basic HTML structure with a `.navbar`, `.content`, and a `.footer`.
2. **CSS Styling:** Styles for visibility transitions, fixed positioning, and ensuring the navbar is initially hidden (`top: -60px`).
3. **JavaScript:**
   - Use `IntersectionObserver` to observe changes in the visibility of the `.content` element and toggle the navbar's visibility when the content enters or exits the viewport.
   - The observer's threshold is set to 0.1, meaning it will trigger actions when at least 10% of the content is visible.
   - A scroll event listener ensures the navbar transitions smoothly during scroll events.
   - The scroll down button is shown only when the content is fully visible and hidden when it is not.

Feel free to adjust `rootMargin` and `threshold` values and the `transition` timings based on your specific requirements to achieve smoother animations and the expected behavior on your longer pages.

