To achieve this behavior for your navigation bar, you can use CSS for styling and JavaScript/jQuery for the scrolling logic. Here’s a basic implementation to help you get started with this functionality:

1. **CSS for the sliding effect and visibility control:**

```css
/* Style for navigation bar */
.navbar {
  transition: top 0.3s;
}

/* Class to hide navbar */
.hidden {
  top: -100px; /* Adjust height according to your navbar */
}
```

2. **JavaScript/jQuery to handle scrolling:**

Ensure you have jQuery loaded in your project.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Responsive Navbar with Scroll Animation</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
</head>
<body>
  <nav class="navbar">Menu</nav>
  <div style="height: 2000px; padding: 100px;">Scroll down</div>
  <div style="height: 2000px; padding: 100px;">Scroll down</div>

  <script src="https://code.jquery.com/jquery-3.6.0.min.js"></script>
  <script>
    $(document).ready(function() {
      let initialTop = $('.navbar').css('top');
      let lastScrollTop = 0;
      let scrollBarThreshold = 50; // Slack before animation
      let navbarHeight = $('.navbar').outerHeight(true);
      let animating = false;

      window.onscroll = function() {
        if (!animating) {
          const scrollTop = $(window).scrollTop();
          let targetTop = initialTop + scrollTop;

          if (Math.abs(targetTop - initialTop) > scrollBarThreshold) {
            if (scrollTop > lastScrollTop && targetTop > lastScrollTop) {
              // Moving Up
              if (targetTop > initialTop) {
                $('.navbar').removeClass('hidden');
                animating = true;
              }

              let height = $('.navbar').outerHeight(true);
              $('.navbar').animate({ top: initTop - (initialTop - height) }, 300, function() {
                animating = false;
              });
            } else {
              // Moving Down
              if (targetTop < initialTop) {
                $('.navbar').addClass('hidden');
                animating = true;
              }
            }

            lastScrollTop = scrollTop;
          }
        }
      }
    });
  </script>
</body>
</html>
```

In this implementation:

- The CSS ensures a smooth transition for the navbar sliding effect and defines a `.hidden` class to hide the navbar when scrolling down.
- The JavaScript/jQuery detects when the page is scrolled. It checks the scroll direction and distance to determine when to show or hide the navbar with a sliding animation.
- The `scrollBarThreshold` variable defines a slack area in pixels after which the sliding animation will be triggered during initial use.

