Creating an iframe element dynamically using server-side Next.js (TypeScript) involves a few steps, where you can create the iframe and pass any necessary attributes or content. Below is a basic example that demonstrates how you can achieve this in a Next.js application using TypeScript.

First, set up your Next.js project. If you haven't done that already, you can create a new project using the following command:
```bash
npx create-next-app@latest my-app
cd my-app
```

Then, change the code as necessary to include an iframe dynamically. This example creates a basic page with a function to render the iframe.

### Step 1: Update `pages/index.tsx`

Open the file `pages/index.tsx` and replace its contents with the following code:

```tsx
import { NextPage, UseStyles } from 'next';
import { useTheme } from 'next-themes';

const Index: NextPage = () => {
  const classes = useStyles();
  const theme = useTheme();

  return (
    <div className={classes.container}>
      <h1 style={{ textAlign: 'center', marginTop: theme === 'light' ? '50px' : '150px' }}>
        Dynamic Iframe Example
      </h1>
      <div id="iframe-container" className={classes.content} style={{ marginTop: '50px' }}>
        <iframe
          id="dynamic-iframe"
          title="Dynamic Iframe"
          src="https://www.example.com"
          style={{ border: '0', width: '100%', height: '500px' }}
        ></iframe>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
};

export default Index;
```

### Step 2: Set up theme provider (Optional)

To make the styling responsive based on the theme, you can optionally include the `next-themes` library which helps with switching themes. If you want to use the theme, install the library first:

```bash
npm install next-themes
```

Then, update `_app.tsx`:

```tsx
import '../styles/globals.css';
import type { AppProps } from 'next/app';
import { ThemeProvider } from 'next-themes';
import type { NextPage } from 'next';

const MyApp: NextPage<AppProps> = ({ Component, pageProps }) => {
  return (
    <html>
      <body>
        <ThemeProvider enableSystem={true} attribute="data-theme">
          <Component {...pageProps} />
        </ThemeProvider>
      </body>
    </html>
  );
};

export default MyApp;
```

### Step 3: Include Global Styles (Optional)

You can include some minimal global styles in `styles/globals.css`:

```css
* {
  margin: 0;
  padding: 0;
  box-sizing: border-box;
}

html {
  font-family: -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, "Segoe UI", Roboto, Helvetica, Arial,
    sans-serif, "Apple Color Emoji", "Segoe UI Emoji", "Segoe UI Symbol";
  font-size: 16px;
  color: #0a0f0d;
}

body {
  height: 100vh;
  display: grid;
  place-items: center;
  background: linear-gradient(135deg, #f3be32, #ed9a9d, #e3a92d);
  background-size: 600% 600%;
  background-attachment: fixed;
  background-position: center;
  background-size: 100% 100%;
  transition: background 0.5s;
}

a {
  text-decoration: none;
  color: inherit;
  transition: 0.4s;
}

a:link, a:visited {
  padding: 10px;
  margin: 1px;
  color: white;
  border: 6px double #fff;
  border-radius: 20px;
  font-size: 25px;
}

a:hover {background: #0a0f0d;}
a:active {background: #0a0f0d;}
#iframe-container {
  padding: 30px;
}

/* You can add more styles here */
```

Now, you have completed a basic structure to create and style a dynamic iframe using Next.js.

### Important Notes
1. Security: Iframes can pose security risks (such as XSS attacks). Always ensure the content within the iframe is from a trusted source.
2. Performance: Embedding third-party sites in iframes can impact the performance and user experience.
3. Mobile Devices: If you target mobile devices, consider responsive design to ensure proper iframe scaling and visibility.

Run your application to see the iframe dynamically embedded and controlled via Next.js.
